{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012XscjcBy118QPxE1Zf2XWy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The working directory exists but is empty (only has a `.logs` directory). I need to build the entire React/TypeScript frontend from scratch. Let me report progress and then start implementing.\n\nBased on the issue:\n- **Component Name:** leave-web-app\n- **Port:** 8080\n- **Dependencies:**\n  - leave-api → `LEAVE_API_URL`\n  - manager-api → `MANAGER_API_URL`\n\nFeatures needed:\n- Employee dashboard with leave balance\n- Leave request submission form\n- Request status tracking\n- Pending request cancellation\n\n\n- Manager dashboard for reviewing requests\n- Approval/rejection with comments\n- User authentication with role-based rendering\n\nI'll use Express to serve the React app and handle the API proxying, since the environment variables are injected at runtime. The Express server can inject these URLs into the React app at build time or serve them through an API endpoint that the frontend calls on load. I need to reconsider the ASDLC guidelines versus the explicit requirement for Express, so I'll go with Express and http-proxy-middleware to handle the routing. Let me sketch out the project structure with the Express server at the root handling both static file serving and API proxying, with the React app in a src directory. I'm settling on a simpler single-package approach where the Express server and React app live together, with the server handling API proxying and static file serving. The server will read environment variables for the leave and manager API endpoints, route requests appropriately, and serve the built React assets from the dist folder, plus expose a health check endpoint.\n\nFor the React app, I'll use relative URLs pointing to `/api/leave` and `/api/manager` so the Express server can intercept and forward them to the actual backend services. Looking at the features, I'm inferring the leave-api probably has endpoints for checking balance, listing requests, submitting new ones, and canceling pending requests, while the manager-api would handle retrieving direct reports' requests and approving them.\n\nSince I don't have the exact API specs, I'll build the frontend with flexible assumptions and focus on getting the auth flow right. I'm thinking a simple login where users enter credentials or an employee ID, get back their role (employee or manager), and store that in React Context for role-based rendering.\n\nNow I'll start building out the full implementation with the workload config, Docker setup, Express server, and React app with TypeScript and Vite.\n\nSetting up the server with http-proxy-middleware... Setting up the proxy routes for both APIs and configuring the Express server to serve the static frontend files with a fallback to index.html for the SPA.\n\nNow I'm planning out the React components—I'll build a TypeScript app with Vite that has a login page where users enter their ID and role, then separate dashboards for employees and managers. I'll use React Context to manage authentication state and make API calls through the proxy routes I just set up.\n\nI'm thinking through the API endpoints both services would likely expose: the leave service needs login, balance retrieval, and request management endpoints, while the manager service needs to handle viewing and approving requests from direct reports. I'll design the frontend to call `/api/leave/*` and `/api/manager/*` generically so it works regardless of the actual backend implementation.\n\nNow I'm ready to start building the app. I'll create a React frontend with a simple login flow that hits the leave API, stores the auth token, and then routes between employee and manager views based on the user's role. For styling, I'll keep it minimal with basic CSS to avoid extra dependencies.\n\nBuilding the React app structure... Now I'm laying out the full implementation plan, starting with the configuration files and then moving through each component and page systematically.\n\nFor the authentication flow, I'll create a login form that posts credentials to the backend and stores the returned user data and token in context and localStorage. The leave balance endpoint will return annual, sick, and casual leave counts, while the leave requests endpoint will provide the list of requests with their statuses.\n\nFor the manager side, I need endpoints to fetch all pending requests and handle approval or rejection with optional comments. Since I don't have the exact API specs, I'm building a reasonable implementation that should work with typical leave management systems. The key thing is making sure the authentication token flows through all requests and that the manager can see requests from their team members.\n\nNow I'm ready to start implementing the code. I'll structure it so the Express server proxies requests to both APIs using the environment variables, and the React frontend makes calls through those proxies.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":506,"cache_read_input_tokens":15508,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":506,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"755a9b6e-46f8-4ab7-8b0d-958937029f65","uuid":"4744fa14-efd3-4369-8ae4-d92796a10c9f"}
